[Term]
id: bervo:BERVO_0000490
name: Surface irrigation magnesium carbonate concentration
def: "The concentration of magnesium carbonate (MgCO3) in the water used for surface irrigation. It represents the amount of magnesium carbonate dissolved in the irrigation water, typically measured in milligrams per liter (mg/L) or parts per million (ppm). This parameter is important for understanding the potential impacts of irrigation on soil chemistry and the overall nutrient balance in agricultural systems. High levels of magnesium carbonate in irrigation water can affect soil pH and fertility, potentially influencing plant growth and crop yields. Monitoring and managing surface irrigation MgCO3 concentration is therefore crucial for sustainable agricultural practices and effective water resource management." []
comment: Definition source - Claude Sonnet 4 through GitHub Copilot in VSCode (Sep 25 2025)
